{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"15a753c8-009d-4802-a548-41151a96ccf3","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet, but I can tell you exactly what you need to configure to publish a C# MCP server as a **dotnet tool** on NuGet.org:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\nAdd these to your `MyMcpServer.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for ...</Description>\n  <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/you/MyMcpServer</PackageProjectUrl>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n  <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Key points\n\n| Property | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `PackAsTool` | Makes it installable via `dotnet tool install` |\n| `ToolCommandName` | The CLI command users will run |\n| `OutputType=Exe` | Required — tools must be executables |\n\n### Publish steps\n\n```bash\n# 1. Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# 2. Push to NuGet.org (get API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install & run it with\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server   # runs via stdio\n```\n\nSince your server uses **stdio transport**, it works naturally as a dotnet tool — the host spawns the process and communicates over stdin/stdout. No additional transport configuration is needed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d3df4252-8ac6-4b52-b7cb-6071924b6c05","outputTokens":512,"requestId":"B019:2B8468:149D588:17053E1:6A027E3A"},"id":"3c6b3108-13b8-4aca-9fdb-4ee603e1cc31","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:11:33.087Z","parentId":"f32c6e96-9bf5-48e1-8f2a-3079b5b1829b"}
